@startuml action_cancel
!theme plain

skinparam backgroundColor white
skinparam sequenceArrowThickness 2
skinparam sequenceParticipantPadding 30
skinparam sequenceBoxPadding 10
skinparam noteFontSize 11

title ROS 2 Action Communication with Cancellation

participant "Action Client" as Client
participant "Action Server\n(MultiThreadedExecutor)" as Server

== Goal Accepted & Executing ==

Client -> Server : send_goal_async(goal)
Server --> Client : GoalHandle (accepted=True)
Client -> Client : _goal_response_callback(future)
Client -> Client : get_result_async() → Future₂

activate Server
Server -> Server : _execute_callback(goal_handle)

Server --> Client : feedback (10%)
Server --> Client : feedback (20%)
Server --> Client : feedback (30%)
Server --> Client : feedback (40%)
Server --> Client : feedback (50%)

== Cancellation ==

Client -> Server : cancel_goal_async()
note right of Client : Returns **cancel Future**

Server -> Server : _cancel_callback(goal_handle)
note right of Server : Returns\nCancelResponse.ACCEPT

Server --> Client : cancel response (goals_canceling > 0)
Client -> Client : _cancel_done_callback(future)
note right of Client : Cancel accepted.\nWait for result.

note over Server #lightyellow
  **On the execute thread:**
  Loop checks is_cancel_requested → True
  Calls goal_handle.canceled()
  Returns Result(success=False)
end note

Server --> Client : Result (STATUS_CANCELED)
deactivate Server

Client -> Client : _result_callback(future₂)
note right of Client : status == STATUS_CANCELED

== Why MultiThreadedExecutor? ==

note over Client, Server #salmon
  The execute callback **blocks** its thread (time.sleep).
  The cancel callback must run on a **different thread**.
  With SingleThreadedExecutor, the cancel callback cannot execute
  → the goal runs to completion and cancellation silently fails.
end note

@enduml
